  4. Chaos theory for flow eddies \'97 Your earlier idea\
\
  This is intellectually interesting but has a fundamental issue for your specific case:\
\
  ALD operates at Re ~ 1\'9610 \'97 completely laminar, no eddies. Chaos and turbulent eddies appear above Re ~ 2300\
  (transition) and fully turbulent above ~ 4000. In ALD's creeping flow, the Navier-Stokes solution is\
  deterministic and smooth \'97 no Lorenz attractors, no strange attractors, no butterfly effects.\
\
  Where it would be valid: Industrial chemical reactors running at Re > 10,000 (mixing vessels, heat exchangers)\
  where turbulent eddies genuinely affect mixing uniformity. Or if you extended your work to high-Re\
  semiconductor plasma etching tools.\
\
  If you want to pursue this idea: The more modern equivalent is Koopman operator theory \'97 linearising nonlinear\
  fluid dynamics for faster simulation. That's an active research area and publishable. But it would require\
  high-Re flow data, not ALD data.\
\
  ---\
  Bottom line\
\
  Your current work is stronger and more novel than the DrivAerNet + custom solver path for the specific problem\
  you're solving. The PhD suggestion is valid general advice for someone building a generic CFD surrogate \'97\
  it's not better advice for ALD topology optimisation specifically.\
\
  The chaos theory idea is the right instinct applied to the wrong regime. Save it for a future paper on high-Re\
  industrial reactor mixing where it would actually apply.\
