\f2 \uc0\u9210 
\f0  Yes \'97 HHL fits directly into this picture. Let me connect all three pieces:\
\
  ---\
  The Chain: Navier-Stokes 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  Koopman 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  HHL\
  \
  Step 1 \'97 The problem with CFD:\
  Navier-Stokes equations are nonlinear PDEs. After discretisation you get a nonlinear system. Classical solvers\
  (like OpenFOAM's SIMPLE/PISO) iterate to convergence \'97 expensive.\
\
  Step 2 \'97 Koopman linearises:\
  Koopman operator theory says: any nonlinear dynamical system can be represented as a linear operator acting on\
  a (possibly infinite-dimensional) space of observable functions. So instead of solving nonlinear NS directly,\
  you lift the system into a higher-dimensional linear space and solve it there.\
\
  Nonlinear NS  
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0   Koopman lifting  
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0   Linear system  Ax = b\
\
  Step 3 \'97 HHL solves Ax = b exponentially faster:\
  The Harrow-Hassidim-Lloyd (HHL) algorithm (2009) solves a linear system Ax = b in O(log N) quantum operations\
  vs O(N) classically (for sparse, well-conditioned A). So:\
\
  Koopman 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  linear system 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  HHL 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  solution\
  Classical: O(N\'b3) 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  Koopman: O(N) 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  HHL: O(log N)\
\
  This is the theoretical chain that makes quantum-accelerated CFD plausible.\
\
